ORDER: As discussed at the conference, the parties' renewed proposal(s) shall be due a week from the date of this order. Tr. at 28:19-23. The Court is hopeful and confident that the parties will be able to submit a joint proposal after meeting and conferring in light of the principles set forth above. However, if disagreement remains, the parties' submission should include a joint description of any remaining areas of disagreement and set forth the parties' competing proposals on that subject. Again, if the Court determines that the remaining gulf between the parties is too wide for the Court to resolve expeditiously, the Court will consider appointing a special master to address the issue. (Signed by Judge Alison J. Nathan on 7/9/2014) (djc) (Entered: 07/09/2014)
562014-07-09
ORDER: The Court is in receipt of the parties' proposals for resolving a potential issue related to diversity jurisdiction highlighted by Judge Oetken's recent opinion in Nomura Asset Acceptance Corp. Alternative Loan Trust, Series 2007-1 v. Nomura Credit & Capital, Inc., No. 13 Civ. 3138 (JPO),- F. Supp. 2d-, 2014 WL 2861479 (S.D.N.Y. June 24, 2014). Dkt. Nos. 53, 54. In light of the parties' submissions, it is hereby ORDERED that: Plaintiff's motion to amend its complaint in order to, inter alia, substitute the trustee as Plaintiff is due by July 28, 2014. Plaintiff should explain whether it believes diversity jurisdiction currently exists notwithstanding Nomura, and also explain why diversity jurisdiction would lie following its proposed amendments. DBSP's opposition is due by August 18, and Plaintiff's reply is due by September 1. The Court also agrees with DBSP that limited discovery on the citizenship of the trusts' beneficiaries has the potential to render any jurisdictional issues moot, and thus obviate any need for the above-described motion practice. Accordingly, the parties are directed to work together to conduct discovery into the citizenship of each trust's beneficiaries, and to complete such discovery by July 28, 2014. If, after such discovery, the parties agree that diversity jurisdiction exists regardless of whether Plaintiff's proposed amendment is effectuated, then they should so indicate in a letter by July 28, and merits discovery will proceed as scheduled. (Signed by Judge Alison J. Nathan on 7/9/2014) (djc) Modified on 7/10/2014 (djc). Modified on 7/11/2014 (djc). (Entered: 07/10/2014)
